# TypeScript comments

Forestrie is a **highly distributed system**. The "why" of local code often
depends on adjacent apps or repositories. Comments must make that context
reachable without duplicating platform docs.

## Principles

1. **Signpost, don't silo.** At file and function level, state how the local
   code fits the wider picture: assumptions about other components, contracts
   honoured, and where to read more. Cross-cutting concerns cannot be inferred
   from local code alone.
2. **Brief with a pointer.** One or two sentences plus a reference is enough
   in most cases. Only the most delicate interactions warrant longer prose.
3. **Explain purpose, not syntax.** Comments describe the **problem** or
   **role** of the following code so human and agent readers can cross-check
   the implementation. Restating what the code literally does is pointless.
4. **Non-obvious details only at line level.** Imperative logic that a typical
   engineer would read straight through needs no comment. Line comments are for
   implementation details that are surprising, constrained, or easy to get
   wrong — not for narrating control flow.
5. **Full coverage of public surfaces.** Every **function**, **method**, and
   **type** (interface, type alias, class, enum) must have a comment describing
   its role and intended use. **Parameters** and **return values** must be
   briefly described in JSDoc `@param` / `@returns` tags where applicable.

## Cross-repo and cross-app signposts

Prefer stable **GitHub blob links** with heading anchors for cross-repo
references:

```typescript
/**
 * Verifies grant inclusion against the owner log's receipt authority.
 * Assumes {@link ReceiptAuthorityResolver} was seeded from Univocity
 * `GET /api/logs/{logId}/public-root` — see
 * [ARC-0019 grant verification](https://github.com/forestrie/devdocs/blob/main/arc/arc-0019-grant-verification-model.md).
 */
```

| Target | Link form |
|--------|-----------|
| Same repo doc | `https://github.com/forestrie/canopy/blob/main/docs/…#anchor` |
| Platform ADR/ARC | `https://github.com/forestrie/devdocs/blob/main/arc/…` or `adr/…` |
| Sibling service | `https://github.com/forestrie/arbor/blob/main/services/…` |
| On-chain behaviour | `https://github.com/forestrie/univocity/blob/main/docs/arc/…` |

Within a comment, name the **remote component** (worker, DO, Go service,
contract method), the **contract** (API route, queue message, env binding,
grant field), and what this code **assumes** vs **guarantees**.

Same-repo implementation detail may use `{@link symbol}` in addition to a doc
link when the symbol is the canonical local entry point.

## What to write at each level

| Level | Comment answers |
|-------|-----------------|
| **File** | What problem this module solves in the distributed flow; primary upstream/downstream dependencies. |
| **Type** | What domain object or boundary this type represents; invariants callers must respect. |
| **Function / method** | What operation this performs in the flow; preconditions, side effects, and error semantics worth knowing. |
| **Stanza** (non-trivial block) | Why this branch or block exists when the surrounding function comment is not enough. |
| **Line** | Only non-obvious mechanics (wire format quirks, platform limits, ordering constraints). |

Good file-level example (from existing practice):

```typescript
/**
 * Grant auth primitives. Two distinct artifacts flow through these helpers —
 * see [grants.md §10](https://github.com/forestrie/canopy/blob/main/docs/grants.md#10-authorization-and-evidence-model).
 * {@link grantAuthorize} verifies from the embedded SCITT receipt only; it does
 * not call the SequencingQueue DO.
 */
```

Bad — restates syntax:

```typescript
// Loop over grants and push each one into the array
for (const grant of grants) {
  result.push(grant);
}
```

Good — non-obvious constraint:

```typescript
// SCRAPI register-grant bodies are CBOR; parent evidence is capped because the
// route is unauthenticated — see MAX_PARENT_GRANT_BODY_SIZE.
```

## Options and config buckets

Describe **options**, **env bindings**, and **config objects** at the
**innermost function that reads each field** — not repeated at every callsite.

- On that function, document **only the fields it uses directly**.
- Each documented field: name, meaning, valid values or source, and behaviour
  when missing or invalid.
- Parent callers may mention that options exist; defer field-level detail to
  the consumer.

```typescript
/**
 * @param options.enforceInclusion — when true, require a verifiable MMR inclusion
 *   proof in the grant receipt; false only in pool-test mode with incomplete
 *   bindings (see forestrie-ingress SequencingQueue configuration).
 */
```

## JSDoc conventions

- Use `/** … */` for files (module banner), types, functions, methods, and
  non-exported constants that encode policy limits.
- Use `@param`, `@returns`, `@throws` sparingly — only when they add contract
  information not obvious from types.
- Use `{@link Name}` for local symbols; markdown links for docs and other repos.
- Keep line length readable; wrap prose naturally (soft wrap ~79 chars is fine).

## When editing

- Adding or changing behaviour that crosses a repo or service boundary → add or
  update signpost comments in the same change.
- Do not copy ARC/ADR prose into source — link and state the local obligation.
- If a function or type lacks a comment, add one before merging.
